issue.title: incorrect notBefore and notAfter dates from HTTPS certificates
issue.body:
When I run LibreSSL to get the dates from a certificate, the notBefore and notAfter dates are today's date and one year from today's date:

```
$ openssl version
LibreSSL 3.3.6
$ openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:443 < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin                           
notBefore=Oct 31 14:08:30 2022 GMT
notAfter=Oct 31 14:08:30 2023 GMT
```

If I run the same command but using `-starttls` on an `imap` or `smtp` server, the dates are correct:
```
$ openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:143 -starttls imap  < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin
notBefore=Sep 28 19:25:08 2022 GMT
notAfter=Dec 27 19:25:07 2022 GMT
```

If I use OpenSSL 3.0.5, the dates are correct for HTTPS certificates:
```
$ /opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3/bin/openssl version
OpenSSL 3.0.5 5 Jul 2022 (Library: OpenSSL 3.0.5 5 Jul 2022)
$ /opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3/bin/openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:443 < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin
notBefore=Sep 28 19:25:08 2022 GMT
notAfter=Dec 27 19:25:07 2022 GMT
```

comment.body:
On Mon, Oct 31, 2022 at 10:04:53AM -0700, Brad Koehn wrote:
> Ahh. It's a `-serverName` issue. If I set the `-serverName` LibreSSL works the way OpenSSL does. Not sure if that makes it a bug or not. 

We only recently switched to including the SNI in s_client to match
this particular aspect of OpenSSL behavior that has confused people a
lot. This is the case since libressl 3.5:

https://github.com/libressl-portable/openbsd/commit/588880daec7326faa0df6c80a9dbb2a273590940

issue.title: regression caught by ruby-openssl test suite
issue.body:
test run: https://github.com/chipitsine/ruby-openssl/actions/runs/3304324758/jobs/5453527017

```
12) Error: test_generalizedtime(OpenSSL::TestASN1): OpenSSL::ASN1::ASN1Error: invalid time format
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode_test'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:435:in `test_generalizedtime'
     432:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 12, 8, 19, 34, 29))
     433:     encode_decode_test B(%w{ 18 0F }) + "99990908234339Z".b,
     434:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(9999, 9, 8, 23, 43, 39))
  => 435:     decode_test B(%w{ 18 0D }) + "201612081934Z".b,
     436:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 12, 8, 19, 34, 0))
     437:     # not implemented
     438:     # decode_test B(%w{ 18 13 }) + "20161208193439+0930".b,

13) Error: test_utctime(OpenSSL::TestASN1): OpenSSL::ASN1::ASN1Error: invalid time format
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode_test'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:408:in `test_utctime'
     405:     encode_decode_test B(%w{ 17 0D }) + "160908234339Z".b,
     406:       OpenSSL::ASN1::UTCTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 9, 8, 23, 43, 39))
     407:     # Seconds is omitted
  => 408:     decode_test B(%w{ 17 0B }) + "1609082343Z".b,
     409:       OpenSSL::ASN1::UTCTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 9, 8, 23, 43, 0))
     410:     begin
     411:       # possible range of UTCTime is 1969-2068 currently

```

comment.body:
This is expected and known. It is a consequence of a deliberate change to make the ASN.1 time parser RFC 5280 compliant https://github.com/libressl-portable/openbsd/commit/eb5d07357320dedccf7ba866d9acfec88d7d1e34. This has stricter requirements than the ASN.1 standard. In particular, the parser no longer accepts times without seconds.

The way these tests are written, openssl-ruby checks for general ASN.1 compliance. In OpenBSD's regress framework, we patch ruby-openssl to provide seconds: https://github.com/openbsd/ports/blob/master/security/openssl-ruby-tests/patches/patch-test_openssl_test_asn1_rb

I should make a pull request to openssl-ruby to skip these tests for libressl 3.6 and later. It is somewhere low on my to do list.

issue.body:
[CVE-2022-37454](https://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2022-37454) affects Python versions prior to 3.11. The fix discussed in [XKCP's advisory](https://github.com/XKCP/XKCP/security/advisories/GHSA-6w4m-2xhg-2658) can be adapted to these versions. The [discoverer's writeup](https://mouha.be/sha-3-buffer-overflow/) contains code that might be turned into regression tests.

Python 3.11 and later switched to using tiny_sha3 in GH-32060, so they should not be affected.

commits.message: use Fn rather than Nm for swab(); from josiah frentsos

Move handshake message handling functions from ssl_both.c to client/server.

Currently, ssl_both.c contains several functions that are used by both the
legacy client and legacy server. This interwines the client and server,
making it harder to make progressive changes. While it does deduplicate
some code, it also ends up with code that is conditioned on s->server and
forces the caller to pass in SSL3_ST_* values.

Move these functions from ssl_both.c into ssl_clnt.c and ssl_srvr.c,
renaming as appropriate and removing the s->server conditionals. Also move
the client and server function prototypes from ssl_locl.h into the .c
files, making them static in the process.

ok tb@

Get rid of SSL_CTX_INTERNAL and SSL_INTERNAL.

These are no longer necessary due to SSL_CTX and SSL now being fully
opaque. Merge SSL_CTX_INTERNAL back into SSL_CTX and SSL_INTERNAL back
into SSL.

Prompted by tb@
Revise for SSL_CTX_INTERNAL and SSL_INTERNAL removal.
Remove unused headers.

Dynamically link libssl for QUIC regress.

Now that the QUIC API is public, we can stop linking this statically.

fix an obvious thinko without serious consequences in the display of e
for rsa and friends.

okay tb@
unwrap two lines for readability
Handle corner case in which the test case can actually be a square
Fix path of mentioned regress test

put the malloc_readonly struct into the "openbsd.mutable" section, so
that the kernel and ld.so will know not to mark it immutable.  malloc
handles the read/write transitions by itself.

Error out if the out secret wasn't properly initialized

Calling HKDF_expand() with a length of 0 happens to succeed due to a quirk
in the API inherited from BoringSSL.  This hides caller-side errors during
development.  Error out to catch such mistakes early on.

ok jsing

Unbreak ASN.1 indefinite length encoding.

In r1.25 of tasn_enc.c a check was added to ensure that asn1_ex_i2c()
returned the same value on both calls, however in the ndef case the len
variable gets changed between calls. Keep a copy of the original value to
test against.

Issue reported by niklas, who encountered a test failure in rust-openssl.

ok miod@ tb@

Avoid potential divide by zero in BIO_dump_indent_cb()

Passing an indent value of 67 results in DUMP_WIDTH_LESS_IDENT returning a
value of zero, which is promptly used for division. Likewise, passing a
value larger than 67 results in a negative value being returned.

Prevent this by limiting indent to 64 (which matches OpenSSL's current
behaviour), as well as ensuring that dump_width is > 0.

Should fix oss-fuzz #52464 and #52467.

ok miod@ tb@

Ensure that verification results in the expected error and error depth.

Improve verification regress and ensure that the legacy or modern
verification completes with the expected error and error depth.

Revise expire callback regress to use chains with expired certificates.

Rather than using X509_STORE_CTX_set_time() (which is resulting all
certificates in the chain being treated as expired), use chains that have
an expired leaf or expired intermediate. This triggers a different code
path, which is currently mishandled (and hence failing).

Also ensure that the resulting error and error depth match what we expect
them to be.

Store errors that result from leaf certificate verification.

In the case that a verification callback is installed that tells the
verifier to continue when a certificate is invalid (e.g. expired),
any error resulting from the leaf certificate verification is not stored
and made available post verification, resulting in an incorrect error being
returned.

Also perform leaf certificate verification prior to adding the chain, which
avoids a potential memory leak (as noted by tb@).

Issue reported by Ilya Shipitsin, who encountered haproxy regress failures.

ok tb@

Remove references to four definitions that tb@ deleted in x509.h rev. 1.89
on Jan 10, 2022: X509_EX_V_INIT X509_EX_V_NETSCAPE_HACK
X509_EXT_PACK_STRING X509_EXT_PACK_UNKNOWN.

Mark BN_set_params and BN_get_params as deprecated, unused,
and intentionally undocumented.

Provide a harness driving rust-openssl's regress tests

rust-openssl is an integral part of the Rust ecosystem and more than a
dozen ports, including lang/rust itself, depend on it. We need to ensure
that it keeps working with LibreSSL.

If the rust and rust-openssl-tests packages are installed, create a cargo
workspace under obj/ that compiles and runs the rust-openssl regress tests
much like what is done for the openssl-ruby tests. This expands our regress
coverage: for instance, this would have caught the broken ASN.1 indefinite
length encoding caused by asn1/tasn_enc.c r1.25.

Positive feedback beck jsing semarie
Testing and ok anton

zlib 1.2.13
Change version number on develop branch to 1.2.12.1.
Silence some warnings from Visual Studio C.
Fix configure issue that discarded provided CC definition.
Fix compile with Windows 10 SDK. (gvollant)

Correct incorrect inputs provided to the CRC functions.

The previous releases of zlib were not sensitive to incorrect CRC
inputs with bits set above the low 32. This commit restores that
behavior, so that applications with such bugs will continue to
operate as before.
Have build test report library version if it doesn't match zlib.h.
Fix missing ZEXPORT for crc32_combine_op().
Fix odd error in Visual C compiler preventing automatic promotion.
Fix inflateBack to detect invalid input with distances too far.
Have infback() deliver all of the available output up to any error.

Fix a bug when getting a gzip header extra field with inflate().

If the extra field was larger than the space the user provided with
inflateGetHeader(), and if multiple calls of inflate() delivered
the extra header data, then there could be a buffer overflow of the
provided space. This commit assures that provided space is not
exceeded.
Add -g when debugging with -fsanitize=address to include symbols.

Fix extra field processing bug that dereferences NULL state->head.

The recent commit to fix a gzip header extra field processing bug
introduced the new bug fixed here.

Fix some typos.

No code changes.
Fix typo in contrib readme.
Avoid conversion warning in minigzip.c.

Fix bug in block type selection when Z_FIXED used.

A fixed block could be chosen when a stored block was smaller. Now
the smaller of the two is always chosen.

Tighten deflateBound bounds.

This improves the non-default expansion from 14% down to 4% in
most cases, and 13% in the remainder.
Add WIN32_LEAN_AND_MEAN for windows.h include.
Add new crc32 functions to z_ prefix defines.

comment.body:
Yes, OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER should never change in LibreSSL. The idea
was to encourage feature checks via autoconf or similar, but that didn't
work out so well.

The ordinary way to check for a LibreSSL version via the preprocessor
would be to use some variant of

#if (defined(LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER) && LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER < 0x3050000fL)

see https://man.openbsd.org/OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER for more details.

issue.title: Improve IPAddressFamily checks
issue.body:
Address the insufficient IPAddressFamily checking #18526 

##### Checklist
<!-- Remove items that do not apply. For completed items, change [ ] to [x]. -->
- [ ] documentation is added or updated
- [ ] tests are added or updated

comment.body:
There is no need to expose it only for a test. Once you have a canonized `IPAddrBlocks`, say `addr`, you can use something like

```cmp_func = sk_IPAddressFamily_set_cmp_func(addr, NULL);```

to retrieve a function pointer to `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` (it should then be restored on `addr` if it is used otherwise).

However, I don't think your capping the length to 3 addresses the problem at hand. If the AFI/SAFI is too long, this will still be quietly ignored and if it is too short, that will also still be accepted.

Since a comparison function can't fail, invalid `IPAddressFamily` (i.e. those with AFI/SAFI of length other than 2 or 3) need to be caught before `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` is called on them.

issue.title: Insufficient IPAddressFamily checking

labels.name: good first issue
labels.description: Bite size change that could be a good start

issue.body:
Reported by @botovq:

Nothing checks that the data member of an `IPAddressFamily` contains a
BIT_STRING of length at most 3. Only `X509v3_addr_get_afi()` establishes
the lower bound of 2. In particular, `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` can compare too
short AFIs or take trailing garbage into account.

comment.body: See also https://github.com/openssl/openssl/issues/18529

The usual idiom to cope with systems not defining socklen_t is to add a
#define socklen_t int
somewhere (or a typedef, whatever gives you an integer type of the size
your system expects as the 3rd argument of accept(2), really).

OpenSSL here is a bit more creative by using an union of an int and a size_t,
and extra code if sizeof(int) != sizeof(size_t) in order to recover the
proper size. With a comment mentioning that this has no chance to work on
a platform with a stack growing up and accept() returning an int, fortunately
this seems to work on HP-UX.

Enable X509_V_FLAG_TRUSTED_FIRST by default in the legacy verifier.

In order to work around the expired DST Root CA X3 certficiate, enable
X509_V_FLAG_TRUSTED_FIRST in the legacy verifier. This means that the
default chain provided by Let's Encrypt will stop at the ISRG Root X1
intermediate, rather than following the DST Root CA X3 intermediate.

small number of things will hit this code path.

add space for the record content. However, in order to do this we need
to determine the length of the record upfront.

This simplifies the code, removes a number of manual bounds checks and
makes way for further improvements.

ok inoguchi@ tb@

Add P-521 to the list of curves supported by default in the client.

A certain VPN provider appears to have configured their servers to only
accept P-521 for TLSv1.3 key exchange. The particular VPN software in use
also does not currently allow for the TLSv1.3 key share groups to be
configured, which means that there is no way to easily use LibreSSL in
this situation.

Include P-521 in the list of curves that are supported by default in the
client, in order to increase interoperability.

Discussed at length with beck@, inoguchi@ and tb@.

ok tb@
Update golden values to match P-521 being enabled by default in the client.

Update golden values to match P-521 being enabled by default in the client.

Diff from tb@
Fix regress test so that it exits non-zero for failure cases.
Update TLS versions to match TLSv1.3 being enabled for TLS_method().

Convert openssl req option handling.

With input from inoguchi@

ok beck@ inoguchi@
Fix some wrapping/indent.

Avoid passing -1 to freezero.

If a peer sends a bogus record consisting of all-zero plaintext,
the content_len would be decremented to -1 and cause a crash in
freezero.

ok inoguchi jsing

I accidentally zeored out a few bytes of the TLSv1.0 session ID.
Restore them to their previous values.

In SSL_new() just 'goto err' on allocation failure.

The error path does the same as the currently duplicated code.

ok inoguchi@ tb@

Use SSL3_SEQUENCE_SIZE for last_write_sequence[] rather than hardcoding.

ok inoguchi@ tb@

Use 0 instead of 0x00 for memset() calls.

ok inoguchi@ tb@

Increment the epoch in the same place for both read and write.

ok inoguchi@ tb@

Send an unexpected message alert if no valid content type is found.

When record protection is engaged, the plaintext must be followed by a
non-zero content type and optional zero padding. If the plaintext is zero
length or only consists of zero bytes then it is not a valid message,
since the content type is unspecified.

ok tb@

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Great, thanks!

OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER should never change in LibreSSL. The idea was to encourage feature checks via autoconf or similar, but that didn't work out so well...

The ordinary way to check for a LibreSSL version via the preprocessor would be to use some variant of

```
#if (defined(LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER) && LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER < 0x3050000fL)
```

see [the manual](https://man.openbsd.org/OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER) or [the `opensslv.h` header](https://github.com/libressl-portable/openbsd/blob/fbf5e3067f7966178941fb933f17dbc145135d50/src/lib/libcrypto/opensslv.h) for more details.

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Thanks for the explanation. It is a bit of a fringe use case, but on the
other hand, a handful of setters more won't make libcrypto fatter than
it already is...

The timing is unfortuante in that we have just entered ABI lock a few
days ago and will release LibreSSL 3.6 soon, so it will definitely be
impossible for you to support LibreSSL 3.5 and 3.6.

If you would be willing to continue supporting LibreSSL <= 3.4 or at
least add back support for LibreSSL 3.7 once it is out (April or May
next year), I will in turn revisit this in the next release cycle. I
will need to discuss with the other developers if we can to add some of
the EVP_CIPHER_meth_set_* functions for 3.7 - I can't take this decision
on my own.

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Could you elaborate on your use case for this?

We generally add pieces of the OpenSSL 1.1 API if we run into software
using them. According to debian codesearch, there are very few things
that make use of the EVP_CIPHER_meth_* setters and getters and even
fewer that have use cases that we want to support. None of the code
paths reached by the OpenBSD ports tree use them. Therefore we haven't
seen a need to add them.

While adding them would be easy enough, it is too late for the 3.6
release.

issue.title: libressl 2.7 adds openbsd 1.1 API
issue.body:
LibreSSL 2.7.0 (2018-03-21) adds the openssl 1.1 API:
https://ftp.openbsd.org/pub/OpenBSD/LibreSSL/libressl-2.7.0-relnotes.txt

This required a bunch of programs to update their `OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER` handling, such as libarchive:
https://bugs.freebsd.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=226853

As far as I know, libressl still supports the OpenSSL 1.0.1 API, so we don't need to change anything yet.  But at some point, we should probably switch over.
(in `lib/crypto/crypto_compat.c`, we assume that any libressl is using the 1.0.1g API)

```
#ifdef LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER
#undef OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER
#define OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER 0x1000107fL
#endif
```

comment.body: LibreSSL 3.6 will ship with `OPENSSL_cleanup()` which should help minimize the pain with using valgrind. We do not, however, install it as an `atexit()` function, applications wanting to use it need to do that themselves.

From Joshua Sing

Prepare to provide OPENSSL_cleanup.

OPENSSL_cleanup() cleans up and deallocates memory in use by the library.
There are a couple of use cases for this, primarily related to memory
leak testing. This will not be called automatically in LibreSSL, which
means that OpenSSL's OPENSSL_NO_INIT_ATEXIT is implied. If code wants to
clean up then they need to explicitly call this themselves.

This avoids asn1_c2i_primitive() from needing knowledge about the internals
of ASN1_INTEGER and ASN1_ENUMERATED.

Ensure ASN.1 types are appropriately encoded.

Per X.690, some ASN.1 types must be primitive encoded, some must be
constructed and some may be either. Add this data to our types table
and check the encoding against this information when decoding.

Stop using CBIGNUM_it internal to libcrypto.

CBIGNUM_it is supposed to be the "clear bignum" or "secure" bignum - that
is one which zeros its memory after use and ensures that the constant time
flags are set... in LibreSSL we always do both of these things for BIGNUMs,
so just use BIGNUM_it instead.

issue.title: incorrect notBefore and notAfter dates from HTTPS certificates
issue.body:
When I run LibreSSL to get the dates from a certificate, the notBefore and notAfter dates are today's date and one year from today's date:

```
$ openssl version
LibreSSL 3.3.6
$ openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:443 < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin                           
notBefore=Oct 31 14:08:30 2022 GMT
notAfter=Oct 31 14:08:30 2023 GMT
```

If I run the same command but using `-starttls` on an `imap` or `smtp` server, the dates are correct:
```
$ openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:143 -starttls imap  < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin
notBefore=Sep 28 19:25:08 2022 GMT
notAfter=Dec 27 19:25:07 2022 GMT
```

If I use OpenSSL 3.0.5, the dates are correct for HTTPS certificates:
```
$ /opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3/bin/openssl version
OpenSSL 3.0.5 5 Jul 2022 (Library: OpenSSL 3.0.5 5 Jul 2022)
$ /opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3/bin/openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:443 < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin
notBefore=Sep 28 19:25:08 2022 GMT
notAfter=Dec 27 19:25:07 2022 GMT
```

issue.title: regression caught by ruby-openssl test suite
issue.body:
test run: https://github.com/chipitsine/ruby-openssl/actions/runs/3304324758/jobs/5453527017

```
12) Error: test_generalizedtime(OpenSSL::TestASN1): OpenSSL::ASN1::ASN1Error: invalid time format
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode_test'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:435:in `test_generalizedtime'
     432:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 12, 8, 19, 34, 29))
     433:     encode_decode_test B(%w{ 18 0F }) + "99990908234339Z".b,
     434:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(9999, 9, 8, 23, 43, 39))
  => 435:     decode_test B(%w{ 18 0D }) + "201612081934Z".b,
     436:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 12, 8, 19, 34, 0))
     437:     # not implemented
     438:     # decode_test B(%w{ 18 13 }) + "20161208193439+0930".b,

13) Error: test_utctime(OpenSSL::TestASN1): OpenSSL::ASN1::ASN1Error: invalid time format
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode_test'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:408:in `test_utctime'
     405:     encode_decode_test B(%w{ 17 0D }) + "160908234339Z".b,
     406:       OpenSSL::ASN1::UTCTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 9, 8, 23, 43, 39))
     407:     # Seconds is omitted
  => 408:     decode_test B(%w{ 17 0B }) + "1609082343Z".b,
     409:       OpenSSL::ASN1::UTCTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 9, 8, 23, 43, 0))
     410:     begin
     411:       # possible range of UTCTime is 1969-2068 currently

```

comment.body:
This is expected and known. It is a consequence of a deliberate change to make the ASN.1 time parser RFC 5280 compliant https://github.com/libressl-portable/openbsd/commit/eb5d07357320dedccf7ba866d9acfec88d7d1e34. This has stricter requirements than the ASN.1 standard. In particular, the parser no longer accepts times without seconds.

The way these tests are written, openssl-ruby checks for general ASN.1 compliance. In OpenBSD's regress framework, we patch ruby-openssl to provide seconds: https://github.com/openbsd/ports/blob/master/security/openssl-ruby-tests/patches/patch-test_openssl_test_asn1_rb

I should make a pull request to openssl-ruby to skip these tests for libressl 3.6 and later. It is somewhere low on my to do list.

issue.body:
[CVE-2022-37454](https://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2022-37454) affects Python versions prior to 3.11. The fix discussed in [XKCP's advisory](https://github.com/XKCP/XKCP/security/advisories/GHSA-6w4m-2xhg-2658) can be adapted to these versions. The [discoverer's writeup](https://mouha.be/sha-3-buffer-overflow/) contains code that might be turned into regression tests.

Python 3.11 and later switched to using tiny_sha3 in GH-32060, so they should not be affected.

commits.message: use Fn rather than Nm for swab(); from josiah frentsos

Move handshake message handling functions from ssl_both.c to client/server.

Currently, ssl_both.c contains several functions that are used by both the
legacy client and legacy server. This interwines the client and server,
making it harder to make progressive changes. While it does deduplicate
some code, it also ends up with code that is conditioned on s->server and
forces the caller to pass in SSL3_ST_* values.

Move these functions from ssl_both.c into ssl_clnt.c and ssl_srvr.c,
renaming as appropriate and removing the s->server conditionals. Also move
the client and server function prototypes from ssl_locl.h into the .c
files, making them static in the process.

ok tb@

Get rid of SSL_CTX_INTERNAL and SSL_INTERNAL.

These are no longer necessary due to SSL_CTX and SSL now being fully
opaque. Merge SSL_CTX_INTERNAL back into SSL_CTX and SSL_INTERNAL back
into SSL.

Prompted by tb@
Revise for SSL_CTX_INTERNAL and SSL_INTERNAL removal.
Remove unused headers.

Dynamically link libssl for QUIC regress.

Now that the QUIC API is public, we can stop linking this statically.

fix an obvious thinko without serious consequences in the display of e
for rsa and friends.

okay tb@
unwrap two lines for readability
Handle corner case in which the test case can actually be a square
Fix path of mentioned regress test

put the malloc_readonly struct into the "openbsd.mutable" section, so
that the kernel and ld.so will know not to mark it immutable.  malloc
handles the read/write transitions by itself.

Error out if the out secret wasn't properly initialized

Calling HKDF_expand() with a length of 0 happens to succeed due to a quirk
in the API inherited from BoringSSL.  This hides caller-side errors during
development.  Error out to catch such mistakes early on.

ok jsing

Unbreak ASN.1 indefinite length encoding.

In r1.25 of tasn_enc.c a check was added to ensure that asn1_ex_i2c()
returned the same value on both calls, however in the ndef case the len
variable gets changed between calls. Keep a copy of the original value to
test against.

Issue reported by niklas, who encountered a test failure in rust-openssl.

ok miod@ tb@

Avoid potential divide by zero in BIO_dump_indent_cb()

Passing an indent value of 67 results in DUMP_WIDTH_LESS_IDENT returning a
value of zero, which is promptly used for division. Likewise, passing a
value larger than 67 results in a negative value being returned.

Prevent this by limiting indent to 64 (which matches OpenSSL's current
behaviour), as well as ensuring that dump_width is > 0.

Should fix oss-fuzz #52464 and #52467.

ok miod@ tb@

Ensure that verification results in the expected error and error depth.

Improve verification regress and ensure that the legacy or modern
verification completes with the expected error and error depth.

Revise expire callback regress to use chains with expired certificates.

Rather than using X509_STORE_CTX_set_time() (which is resulting all
certificates in the chain being treated as expired), use chains that have
an expired leaf or expired intermediate. This triggers a different code
path, which is currently mishandled (and hence failing).

Also ensure that the resulting error and error depth match what we expect
them to be.

Store errors that result from leaf certificate verification.

In the case that a verification callback is installed that tells the
verifier to continue when a certificate is invalid (e.g. expired),
any error resulting from the leaf certificate verification is not stored
and made available post verification, resulting in an incorrect error being
returned.

Also perform leaf certificate verification prior to adding the chain, which
avoids a potential memory leak (as noted by tb@).

Issue reported by Ilya Shipitsin, who encountered haproxy regress failures.

ok tb@

Remove references to four definitions that tb@ deleted in x509.h rev. 1.89
on Jan 10, 2022: X509_EX_V_INIT X509_EX_V_NETSCAPE_HACK
X509_EXT_PACK_STRING X509_EXT_PACK_UNKNOWN.

Mark BN_set_params and BN_get_params as deprecated, unused,
and intentionally undocumented.

Provide a harness driving rust-openssl's regress tests

rust-openssl is an integral part of the Rust ecosystem and more than a
dozen ports, including lang/rust itself, depend on it. We need to ensure
that it keeps working with LibreSSL.

If the rust and rust-openssl-tests packages are installed, create a cargo
workspace under obj/ that compiles and runs the rust-openssl regress tests
much like what is done for the openssl-ruby tests. This expands our regress
coverage: for instance, this would have caught the broken ASN.1 indefinite
length encoding caused by asn1/tasn_enc.c r1.25.

commit 0258c1b1eb178f761b71f0eafb7ab61a552a7cdf
Author: tb <tb@openbsd.org>
Date:   Thu Jul 22 16:40:19 2021 +0000

    Add sizes for free() in zlib

    Rebased version of a diff from miod who described it as follows:

    This tries to keep diffability against upstream, hence a
questionable
    choice of the size type for zcfree() - but all sizes should fit in
32
    bits anyway.

    Since all zcfree routines used in the tree cope with NULL arguments
    (including the various alloc.c used by the boot blocks), I have
    simplified TRY_FREE to compensate for the growth.

    Reminded by and ok mpi

zlib 1.2.13
Change version number on develop branch to 1.2.12.1.
Silence some warnings from Visual Studio C.
Fix configure issue that discarded provided CC definition.
Fix compile with Windows 10 SDK. (gvollant)

Correct incorrect inputs provided to the CRC functions.

The previous releases of zlib were not sensitive to incorrect CRC
inputs with bits set above the low 32. This commit restores that
behavior, so that applications with such bugs will continue to
operate as before.
Have build test report library version if it doesn't match zlib.h.
Fix missing ZEXPORT for crc32_combine_op().
Fix odd error in Visual C compiler preventing automatic promotion.
Fix inflateBack to detect invalid input with distances too far.
Have infback() deliver all of the available output up to any error.

Fix a bug when getting a gzip header extra field with inflate().

If the extra field was larger than the space the user provided with
inflateGetHeader(), and if multiple calls of inflate() delivered
the extra header data, then there could be a buffer overflow of the
provided space. This commit assures that provided space is not
exceeded.
Add -g when debugging with -fsanitize=address to include symbols.

Fix extra field processing bug that dereferences NULL state->head.

The recent commit to fix a gzip header extra field processing bug
introduced the new bug fixed here.

Fix some typos.

No code changes.
Fix typo in contrib readme.
Avoid conversion warning in minigzip.c.

Fix bug in block type selection when Z_FIXED used.

A fixed block could be chosen when a stored block was smaller. Now
the smaller of the two is always chosen.

Tighten deflateBound bounds.

This improves the non-default expansion from 14% down to 4% in
most cases, and 13% in the remainder.
Add WIN32_LEAN_AND_MEAN for windows.h include.
Add new crc32 functions to z_ prefix defines.

comment.body:
Yes, OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER should never change in LibreSSL. The idea
was to encourage feature checks via autoconf or similar, but that didn't
work out so well.

The ordinary way to check for a LibreSSL version via the preprocessor
would be to use some variant of

#if (defined(LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER) && LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER < 0x3050000fL)

see https://man.openbsd.org/OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER for more details.

issue.title: Improve IPAddressFamily checks
issue.body:
Address the insufficient IPAddressFamily checking #18526 

##### Checklist
<!-- Remove items that do not apply. For completed items, change [ ] to [x]. -->
- [ ] documentation is added or updated
- [ ] tests are added or updated

comment.body:
There is no need to expose it only for a test. Once you have a canonized `IPAddrBlocks`, say `addr`, you can use something like

```cmp_func = sk_IPAddressFamily_set_cmp_func(addr, NULL);```

to retrieve a function pointer to `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` (it should then be restored on `addr` if it is used otherwise).

However, I don't think your capping the length to 3 addresses the problem at hand. If the AFI/SAFI is too long, this will still be quietly ignored and if it is too short, that will also still be accepted.

Since a comparison function can't fail, invalid `IPAddressFamily` (i.e. those with AFI/SAFI of length other than 2 or 3) need to be caught before `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` is called on them.

issue.title: Insufficient IPAddressFamily checking

labels.name: good first issue
labels.description: Bite size change that could be a good start

issue.body:
Reported by @botovq:

Nothing checks that the data member of an `IPAddressFamily` contains a
BIT_STRING of length at most 3. Only `X509v3_addr_get_afi()` establishes
the lower bound of 2. In particular, `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` can compare too
short AFIs or take trailing garbage into account.

comment.body: See also https://github.com/openssl/openssl/issues/18529

Turn the validation_err() macro into a function

validation_err() is an ugly macro with side effects and a goto in it.
At the cost of a few lines of code we can turn this into a function
where the side effects are explicit and ret is now explicitly set in
the main body of addr_validate_path_internal().

We get to a point where it is halfway possible to reason about the
convoluted control flow in this function.

The usual idiom to cope with systems not defining socklen_t is to add a
#define socklen_t int
somewhere (or a typedef, whatever gives you an integer type of the size
your system expects as the 3rd argument of accept(2), really).

OpenSSL here is a bit more creative by using an union of an int and a size_t,
and extra code if sizeof(int) != sizeof(size_t) in order to recover the
proper size. With a comment mentioning that this has no chance to work on
a platform with a stack growing up and accept() returning an int, fortunately
this seems to work on HP-UX.

Switch to the light side of the force and declare and use socklen_t variables,
period. If your system does not define socklen_t, consider bringing it back
to your vendor for a refund.

Enable X509_V_FLAG_TRUSTED_FIRST by default in the legacy verifier.

In order to work around the expired DST Root CA X3 certficiate, enable
X509_V_FLAG_TRUSTED_FIRST in the legacy verifier. This means that the
default chain provided by Let's Encrypt will stop at the ISRG Root X1
intermediate, rather than following the DST Root CA X3 intermediate.

Note that the new verifier does not suffer from this issue, so only a
small number of things will hit this code path.

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Great, thanks!

OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER should never change in LibreSSL. The idea was to encourage feature checks via autoconf or similar, but that didn't work out so well...

The ordinary way to check for a LibreSSL version via the preprocessor would be to use some variant of

```
#if (defined(LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER) && LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER < 0x3050000fL)
```

see [the manual](https://man.openbsd.org/OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER) or [the `opensslv.h` header](https://github.com/libressl-portable/openbsd/blob/fbf5e3067f7966178941fb933f17dbc145135d50/src/lib/libcrypto/opensslv.h) for more details.

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Thanks for the explanation. It is a bit of a fringe use case, but on the
other hand, a handful of setters more won't make libcrypto fatter than
it already is...

The timing is unfortuante in that we have just entered ABI lock a few
days ago and will release LibreSSL 3.6 soon, so it will definitely be
impossible for you to support LibreSSL 3.5 and 3.6.

If you would be willing to continue supporting LibreSSL <= 3.4 or at
least add back support for LibreSSL 3.7 once it is out (April or May
next year), I will in turn revisit this in the next release cycle. I
will need to discuss with the other developers if we can to add some of
the EVP_CIPHER_meth_set_* functions for 3.7 - I can't take this decision
on my own.

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Could you elaborate on your use case for this?

We generally add pieces of the OpenSSL 1.1 API if we run into software
using them. According to debian codesearch, there are very few things
that make use of the EVP_CIPHER_meth_* setters and getters and even
fewer that have use cases that we want to support. None of the code
paths reached by the OpenBSD ports tree use them. Therefore we haven't
seen a need to add them.

While adding them would be easy enough, it is too late for the 3.6
release.

issue.title: libressl 2.7 adds openbsd 1.1 API
issue.body:
LibreSSL 2.7.0 (2018-03-21) adds the openssl 1.1 API:
https://ftp.openbsd.org/pub/OpenBSD/LibreSSL/libressl-2.7.0-relnotes.txt

This required a bunch of programs to update their `OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER` handling, such as libarchive:
https://bugs.freebsd.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=226853

As far as I know, libressl still supports the OpenSSL 1.0.1 API, so we don't need to change anything yet.  But at some point, we should probably switch over.
(in `lib/crypto/crypto_compat.c`, we assume that any libressl is using the 1.0.1g API)

```
#ifdef LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER
#undef OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER
#define OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER 0x1000107fL
#endif
```

comment.body: LibreSSL 3.6 will ship with `OPENSSL_cleanup()` which should help minimize the pain with using valgrind. We do not, however, install it as an `atexit()` function, applications wanting to use it need to do that themselves.

With https://github.com/openbsd/src/commit/b81859533eb46037002fc92de8c3a7d0c2cc5d5f the call to `EVP_CIPHER_CTX_reset()` can no longer fail, so I consider this issue resolved. From Joshua Sing

Prepare to provide OPENSSL_cleanup.

OPENSSL_cleanup() cleans up and deallocates memory in use by the library.
There are a couple of use cases for this, primarily related to memory
leak testing. This will not be called automatically in LibreSSL, which
means that OpenSSL's OPENSSL_NO_INIT_ATEXIT is implied. If code wants to
clean up then they need to explicitly call this themselves.

Rewrite RMD-160 tests to be table-driven.

From Joshua Sing

Stop using CBIGNUM_it internal to libcrypto.

CBIGNUM_it is supposed to be the "clear bignum" or "secure" bignum - that
is one which zeros its memory after use and ensures that the constant time
flags are set... in LibreSSL we always do both of these things for BIGNUMs,
so just use BIGNUM_it instead.

ok tb@
Adjust for Joshua Sing's test replacements

issue.title: incorrect notBefore and notAfter dates from HTTPS certificates
issue.body:
When I run LibreSSL to get the dates from a certificate, the notBefore and notAfter dates are today's date and one year from today's date:

```
$ openssl version
LibreSSL 3.3.6
$ openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:443 < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin                           
notBefore=Oct 31 14:08:30 2022 GMT
notAfter=Oct 31 14:08:30 2023 GMT
```

If I run the same command but using `-starttls` on an `imap` or `smtp` server, the dates are correct:
```
$ openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:143 -starttls imap  < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin
notBefore=Sep 28 19:25:08 2022 GMT
notAfter=Dec 27 19:25:07 2022 GMT
```

If I use OpenSSL 3.0.5, the dates are correct for HTTPS certificates:
```
$ /opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3/bin/openssl version
OpenSSL 3.0.5 5 Jul 2022 (Library: OpenSSL 3.0.5 5 Jul 2022)
$ /opt/homebrew/opt/openssl@3/bin/openssl s_client -connect mail.koehn.com:443 < /dev/null 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -dates -noout -in /dev/stdin
notBefore=Sep 28 19:25:08 2022 GMT
notAfter=Dec 27 19:25:07 2022 GMT
```

comment.body:
On Mon, Oct 31, 2022 at 10:04:53AM -0700, Brad Koehn wrote:
> Ahh. It's a `-serverName` issue. If I set the `-serverName` LibreSSL works the way OpenSSL does. Not sure if that makes it a bug or not. 

We only recently switched to including the SNI in s_client to match
this particular aspect of OpenSSL behavior that has confused people a
lot. This is the case since libressl 3.5:

https://github.com/libressl-portable/openbsd/commit/588880daec7326faa0df6c80a9dbb2a273590940

issue.title: regression caught by ruby-openssl test suite
issue.body:
test run: https://github.com/chipitsine/ruby-openssl/actions/runs/3304324758/jobs/5453527017

```
12) Error: test_generalizedtime(OpenSSL::TestASN1): OpenSSL::ASN1::ASN1Error: invalid time format
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode_test'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:435:in `test_generalizedtime'
     432:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 12, 8, 19, 34, 29))
     433:     encode_decode_test B(%w{ 18 0F }) + "99990908234339Z".b,
     434:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(9999, 9, 8, 23, 43, 39))
  => 435:     decode_test B(%w{ 18 0D }) + "201612081934Z".b,
     436:       OpenSSL::ASN1::GeneralizedTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 12, 8, 19, 34, 0))
     437:     # not implemented
     438:     # decode_test B(%w{ 18 13 }) + "20161208193439+0930".b,

13) Error: test_utctime(OpenSSL::TestASN1): OpenSSL::ASN1::ASN1Error: invalid time format
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:700:in `decode_test'
/home/runner/work/ruby-openssl/ruby-openssl/test/openssl/test_asn1.rb:408:in `test_utctime'
     405:     encode_decode_test B(%w{ 17 0D }) + "160908234339Z".b,
     406:       OpenSSL::ASN1::UTCTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 9, 8, 23, 43, 39))
     407:     # Seconds is omitted
  => 408:     decode_test B(%w{ 17 0B }) + "1609082343Z".b,
     409:       OpenSSL::ASN1::UTCTime.new(Time.utc(2016, 9, 8, 23, 43, 0))
     410:     begin
     411:       # possible range of UTCTime is 1969-2068 currently

```

comment.body:
This is expected and known. It is a consequence of a deliberate change to make the ASN.1 time parser RFC 5280 compliant https://github.com/libressl-portable/openbsd/commit/eb5d07357320dedccf7ba866d9acfec88d7d1e34. This has stricter requirements than the ASN.1 standard. In particular, the parser no longer accepts times without seconds.

The way these tests are written, openssl-ruby checks for general ASN.1 compliance. In OpenBSD's regress framework, we patch ruby-openssl to provide seconds: https://github.com/openbsd/ports/blob/master/security/openssl-ruby-tests/patches/patch-test_openssl_test_asn1_rb

I should make a pull request to openssl-ruby to skip these tests for libressl 3.6 and later. It is somewhere low on my to do list.

This is a port of the applicable part of [XKCP's fix][1] for CVE-2022-37454 and avoids the segmentation fault and the infinite loop in the test cases published [by the discoverer][2].

[1]: https://github.com/XKCP/XKCP/commit/fdc6fef075f4e81d6b1bc38364248975e08e340a
[2]: https://mouha.be/sha-3-buffer-overflow/

Thanks for your contribution!
Please read this comment in its entirety. It's quite important.

# Pull Request title

It should be in the following format:

```
gh-NNNNN: Summary of the changes made
```

Where: gh-NNNNN refers to the GitHub issue number.

Most PRs will require an issue number. Trivial changes, like fixing a typo, do not need an issue.

# Backport Pull Request title

If this is a backport PR (PR made against branches other than `main`),
please ensure that the PR title is in the following format:

```

```

Where: [X.Y] is the branch name, e.g. [3.6].

GH-NNNN refers to the PR number from `main`.

issue.body:
[CVE-2022-37454](https://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2022-37454) affects Python versions prior to 3.11. The fix discussed in [XKCP's advisory](https://github.com/XKCP/XKCP/security/advisories/GHSA-6w4m-2xhg-2658) can be adapted to these versions. The [discoverer's writeup](https://mouha.be/sha-3-buffer-overflow/) contains code that might be turned into regression tests.

Python 3.11 and later switched to using tiny_sha3 in GH-32060, so they should not be affected.

comment.body:
And here are instructions to select the correct library to link against:

https://docs.rs/openssl/latest/openssl/#manual

On Fri, Oct 21, 2022 at 03:36:24AM -0700, shipitsin-ilia wrote:
> @botovq , can you please share details how to run those regress tests ?
> I think, I can add them to github pipeline

Thanks, that would be nice. I think the easiest is to install git and
rust from the distribution, then do:

$ git clone https://github.com/sfackler/rust-openssl.git
$ cd rust-openssl

Since rust-openssl only supports the latest stable releases, we will
need this patch which will need adjusting for every major version:

https://github.com/openbsd/ports/blob/master/security/rust-openssl-tests/patches/patch-openssl-sys_build_main_rs

Then inspect the return value of 

$ cargo test

commits.message: use Fn rather than Nm for swab(); from josiah frentsos

Move handshake message handling functions from ssl_both.c to client/server.

Currently, ssl_both.c contains several functions that are used by both the
legacy client and legacy server. This interwines the client and server,
making it harder to make progressive changes. While it does deduplicate
some code, it also ends up with code that is conditioned on s->server and
forces the caller to pass in SSL3_ST_* values.

Move these functions from ssl_both.c into ssl_clnt.c and ssl_srvr.c,
renaming as appropriate and removing the s->server conditionals. Also move
the client and server function prototypes from ssl_locl.h into the .c
files, making them static in the process.

ok tb@

Get rid of SSL_CTX_INTERNAL and SSL_INTERNAL.

These are no longer necessary due to SSL_CTX and SSL now being fully
opaque. Merge SSL_CTX_INTERNAL back into SSL_CTX and SSL_INTERNAL back
into SSL.

Prompted by tb@
Revise for SSL_CTX_INTERNAL and SSL_INTERNAL removal.
Remove unused headers.

Dynamically link libssl for QUIC regress.

Now that the QUIC API is public, we can stop linking this statically.

fix an obvious thinko without serious consequences in the display of e
for rsa and friends.

okay tb@
unwrap two lines for readability
Handle corner case in which the test case can actually be a square
Fix path of mentioned regress test

put the malloc_readonly struct into the "openbsd.mutable" section, so
that the kernel and ld.so will know not to mark it immutable.  malloc
handles the read/write transitions by itself.

Error out if the out secret wasn't properly initialized

Calling HKDF_expand() with a length of 0 happens to succeed due to a quirk
in the API inherited from BoringSSL.  This hides caller-side errors during
development.  Error out to catch such mistakes early on.

ok jsing

Unbreak ASN.1 indefinite length encoding.

In r1.25 of tasn_enc.c a check was added to ensure that asn1_ex_i2c()
returned the same value on both calls, however in the ndef case the len
variable gets changed between calls. Keep a copy of the original value to
test against.

Issue reported by niklas, who encountered a test failure in rust-openssl.

ok miod@ tb@

Avoid potential divide by zero in BIO_dump_indent_cb()

Passing an indent value of 67 results in DUMP_WIDTH_LESS_IDENT returning a
value of zero, which is promptly used for division. Likewise, passing a
value larger than 67 results in a negative value being returned.

Prevent this by limiting indent to 64 (which matches OpenSSL's current
behaviour), as well as ensuring that dump_width is > 0.

Should fix oss-fuzz #52464 and #52467.

ok miod@ tb@

Ensure that verification results in the expected error and error depth.

Improve verification regress and ensure that the legacy or modern
verification completes with the expected error and error depth.

Revise expire callback regress to use chains with expired certificates.

Rather than using X509_STORE_CTX_set_time() (which is resulting all
certificates in the chain being treated as expired), use chains that have
an expired leaf or expired intermediate. This triggers a different code
path, which is currently mishandled (and hence failing).

Also ensure that the resulting error and error depth match what we expect
them to be.

Store errors that result from leaf certificate verification.

In the case that a verification callback is installed that tells the
verifier to continue when a certificate is invalid (e.g. expired),
any error resulting from the leaf certificate verification is not stored
and made available post verification, resulting in an incorrect error being
returned.

Also perform leaf certificate verification prior to adding the chain, which
avoids a potential memory leak (as noted by tb@).

Issue reported by Ilya Shipitsin, who encountered haproxy regress failures.

ok tb@

Remove references to four definitions that tb@ deleted in x509.h rev. 1.89
on Jan 10, 2022: X509_EX_V_INIT X509_EX_V_NETSCAPE_HACK
X509_EXT_PACK_STRING X509_EXT_PACK_UNKNOWN.

Mark BN_set_params and BN_get_params as deprecated, unused,
and intentionally undocumented.

Provide a harness driving rust-openssl's regress tests

rust-openssl is an integral part of the Rust ecosystem and more than a
dozen ports, including lang/rust itself, depend on it. We need to ensure
that it keeps working with LibreSSL.

If the rust and rust-openssl-tests packages are installed, create a cargo
workspace under obj/ that compiles and runs the rust-openssl regress tests
much like what is done for the openssl-ruby tests. This expands our regress
coverage: for instance, this would have caught the broken ASN.1 indefinite
length encoding caused by asn1/tasn_enc.c r1.25.

Positive feedback beck jsing semarie
Testing and ok anton
Link rust-openssl to regress

Store errors that result from leaf certificate verification.

In the case that a verification callback is installed that tells the
verifier to continue when a certificate is invalid (e.g. expired),
any error resulting from the leaf certificate verification is not stored
and made available post verification, resulting in an incorrect error being
returned.

Also perform leaf certificate verification prior to adding the chain, which
avoids a potential memory leak (as noted by tb@).

Issue reported by Ilya Shipitsin, who encountered haproxy regress failures.

ok tb@; from jsing

This is errata/7.2/001_x509.patch.sig

Unbreak ASN.1 indefinite length encoding.

In r1.25 of tasn_enc.c a check was added to ensure that asn1_ex_i2c()
returned the same value on both calls, however in the ndef case the len
variable gets changed between calls. Keep a copy of the original value to
test against.

Issue reported by niklas, who encountered a test failure in rust-openssl.

ok miod@ tb@; from jsing

This is errata/7.2/002_asn1.patch.sig

Install rust and rust-openssl-tests

Change version number on develop branch to 1.2.12.1.
Silence some warnings from Visual Studio C.
Fix configure issue that discarded provided CC definition.
Fix compile with Windows 10 SDK. (gvollant)

Correct incorrect inputs provided to the CRC functions.

The previous releases of zlib were not sensitive to incorrect CRC
inputs with bits set above the low 32. This commit restores that
behavior, so that applications with such bugs will continue to
operate as before.
Have build test report library version if it doesn't match zlib.h.
Fix missing ZEXPORT for crc32_combine_op().
Fix odd error in Visual C compiler preventing automatic promotion.
Fix inflateBack to detect invalid input with distances too far.
Have infback() deliver all of the available output up to any error.

Fix a bug when getting a gzip header extra field with inflate().

If the extra field was larger than the space the user provided with
inflateGetHeader(), and if multiple calls of inflate() delivered
the extra header data, then there could be a buffer overflow of the
provided space. This commit assures that provided space is not
exceeded.
Add -g when debugging with -fsanitize=address to include symbols.

Fix extra field processing bug that dereferences NULL state->head.

The recent commit to fix a gzip header extra field processing bug
introduced the new bug fixed here.

Fix some typos.

No code changes.
Fix typo in contrib readme.
Avoid conversion warning in minigzip.c.

Fix bug in block type selection when Z_FIXED used.

A fixed block could be chosen when a stored block was smaller. Now
the smaller of the two is always chosen.

Tighten deflateBound bounds.

This improves the non-default expansion from 14% down to 4% in
most cases, and 13% in the remainder.
Add WIN32_LEAN_AND_MEAN for windows.h include.
Add new crc32 functions to z_ prefix defines.

comment.body:
Yes, OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER should never change in LibreSSL. The idea
was to encourage feature checks via autoconf or similar, but that didn't
work out so well.

The ordinary way to check for a LibreSSL version via the preprocessor
would be to use some variant of

#if (defined(LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER) && LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER < 0x3050000fL)

see https://man.openbsd.org/OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER for more details.

issue.title: Improve IPAddressFamily checks
issue.body:
Address the insufficient IPAddressFamily checking #18526 

##### Checklist
<!-- Remove items that do not apply. For completed items, change [ ] to [x]. -->
- [ ] documentation is added or updated
- [ ] tests are added or updated

comment.body:
There is no need to expose it only for a test. Once you have a canonized `IPAddrBlocks`, say `addr`, you can use something like

```cmp_func = sk_IPAddressFamily_set_cmp_func(addr, NULL);```

to retrieve a function pointer to `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` (it should then be restored on `addr` if it is used otherwise).

However, I don't think your capping the length to 3 addresses the problem at hand. If the AFI/SAFI is too long, this will still be quietly ignored and if it is too short, that will also still be accepted.

Since a comparison function can't fail, invalid `IPAddressFamily` (i.e. those with AFI/SAFI of length other than 2 or 3) need to be caught before `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` is called on them.

issue.title: Insufficient IPAddressFamily checking

labels.name: good first issue
labels.description: Bite size change that could be a good start

issue.body:
Reported by @botovq:

Nothing checks that the data member of an `IPAddressFamily` contains a
BIT_STRING of length at most 3. Only `X509v3_addr_get_afi()` establishes
the lower bound of 2. In particular, `IPAddressFamily_cmp()` can compare too
short AFIs or take trailing garbage into account.

comment.body: See also https://github.com/openssl/openssl/issues/18529

The usual idiom to cope with systems not defining socklen_t is to add a
#define socklen_t int
somewhere (or a typedef, whatever gives you an integer type of the size
your system expects as the 3rd argument of accept(2), really).

OpenSSL here is a bit more creative by using an union of an int and a size_t,
and extra code if sizeof(int) != sizeof(size_t) in order to recover the
proper size. With a comment mentioning that this has no chance to work on
a platform with a stack growing up and accept() returning an int, fortunately
this seems to work on HP-UX.

Switch to the light side of the force and declare and use socklen_t variables,
period. If your system does not define socklen_t, consider bringing it back
to your vendor for a refund.

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Great, thanks!

OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER should never change in LibreSSL. The idea was to encourage feature checks via autoconf or similar, but that didn't work out so well...

The ordinary way to check for a LibreSSL version via the preprocessor would be to use some variant of

```
#if (defined(LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER) && LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER < 0x3050000fL)
```

see [the manual](https://man.openbsd.org/OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER) or [the `opensslv.h` header](https://github.com/libressl-portable/openbsd/blob/fbf5e3067f7966178941fb933f17dbc145135d50/src/lib/libcrypto/opensslv.h) for more details.

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Thanks for the explanation. It is a bit of a fringe use case, but on the
other hand, a handful of setters more won't make libcrypto fatter than
it already is...

The timing is unfortuante in that we have just entered ABI lock a few
days ago and will release LibreSSL 3.6 soon, so it will definitely be
impossible for you to support LibreSSL 3.5 and 3.6.

If you would be willing to continue supporting LibreSSL <= 3.4 or at
least add back support for LibreSSL 3.7 once it is out (April or May
next year), I will in turn revisit this in the next release cycle. I
will need to discuss with the other developers if we can to add some of
the EVP_CIPHER_meth_set_* functions for 3.7 - I can't take this decision
on my own.

issue.title: EVP_CIPHER Opacity

comment.body:
Could you elaborate on your use case for this?

We generally add pieces of the OpenSSL 1.1 API if we run into software
using them. According to debian codesearch, there are very few things
that make use of the EVP_CIPHER_meth_* setters and getters and even
fewer that have use cases that we want to support. None of the code
paths reached by the OpenBSD ports tree use them. Therefore we haven't
seen a need to add them.

While adding them would be easy enough, it is too late for the 3.6
release.

issue.title: libressl 2.7 adds openbsd 1.1 API
issue.body:
LibreSSL 2.7.0 (2018-03-21) adds the openssl 1.1 API:
https://ftp.openbsd.org/pub/OpenBSD/LibreSSL/libressl-2.7.0-relnotes.txt

This required a bunch of programs to update their `OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER` handling, such as libarchive:
https://bugs.freebsd.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=226853

As far as I know, libressl still supports the OpenSSL 1.0.1 API, so we don't need to change anything yet.  But at some point, we should probably switch over.
(in `lib/crypto/crypto_compat.c`, we assume that any libressl is using the 1.0.1g API)

```
#ifdef LIBRESSL_VERSION_NUMBER
#undef OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER
#define OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER 0x1000107fL
#endif
```

comment.body: LibreSSL 3.6 will ship with `OPENSSL_cleanup()` which should help minimize the pain with using valgrind. We do not, however, install it as an `atexit()` function, applications wanting to use it need to do that themselves.

```

Fixed in
https://github.com/openbsd/src/commit/44c8d4d1d7594fa7b3992060118f67d0b6804f75

```
** CID 356776:  Error handling issues  (CHECKED_RETURN)
/home/runner/work/portable/portable/crypto/cms/cms_kari.c: 274 in cms_kek_cipher()
[...]
>>>     CID 356776:  Error handling issues  (CHECKED_RETURN)
>>>     Calling "EVP_CIPHER_CTX_reset" without checking return value (as is done elsewhere 4 out of 5 times).
274             EVP_CIPHER_CTX_reset(kari->ctx);
```

While this could easily be fixed, the real fix is to make sure that `EVP_CIPHER_CTX_reset()` can't actually fail.
An actual [failure](https://github.com/openbsd/src/blob/81ef01623ab77afbddf61dd8700a4241cbda76d9/lib/libcrypto/evp/evp_enc.c#L595-L605) will currently result in a leak...

```
>>>     CID 356775:  Incorrect expression  (COPY_PASTE_ERROR)
>>>     "out_len" in "&out_len" looks like a copy-paste error.
411             if (!EVP_DecryptFinal_ex(ctx, out + total_len, &out_len)) {
```

This looks correct to me.

commits.message:
Add output length validation for EVP

From Joshua Sing

Add EVP test coverage for RC2.

From Joshua Sing

ssl_cipher_process_rulestr: don't read outside rule_str buffer
If rule_str ended in a "-", "l" was incremented one byte past the
end of the buffer.  This resulted in an out-of-bounds read when "l"
is dereferenced at the end of the loop.  OK tb@

ssl_cipher_process_rulestr: return early if a cipher command is invalid
This is a safer fix for the bug where we might read outside rule_str
buffer and is how BoringSSL fixed it.  OK tb@

fix repeated words
ok miod@ jmc@

fix repeated words
ok ok miod@ ack ack jmc@

carrier return character -> carriage return character
ok jmc@ miod@

Provide a version of ssl_msg_callback() that takes a CBS.

Use this from the TLSv1.3 code.

ok tb@

Use CBS to parse TLS alerts in the legacy stack.

ok tb@

Use correct length for EVP CFB mode ciphers.

The BLOCK_CIPHER_* macros contained a bug where the total length is passed
to the underlying cipher implementation, rather than the length of the
current chunk. Correct this and use the chunk length instead.

Should address the remaining issues reported by Coverity.

ok tb@

Increment the input and output position for EVP AES CFB1.

The length is decremented, however the input is repeatedly read from and
output written to the same position. Correct this by actually incrementing
the input and output pointers.

Found via OpenSSL 604e591ed7,

ok tb@
fix repeated words

Stop casting a size_t to a long and then passing it as a size_t.

These cipher implementations take a size_t length argument, so stop
casting it to a long.

Found by Coverity.

ok tb@

Replace aes_{ccm,xts}_cleanup usage with NULL.

Only change in generated assembly is due to line numbers.

Remove more mkerr.pl remnants, missed in previous

Noticed by jsg
Feedback OK jsg

Add a table-driven test for RC2 in ECB mode to replace the old one.

From Joshua Sing
Regen bio.h.patch
Switch to new rc2_test

commits.message: cast time_t to long long before printing for portability
Convert from %i to %d
More long long casts for printing time_t
Two more missing long long casts
Plug leaks due to not resetting the EVP_CIPHER_CTX
Fix copy-paste error
Drop long long casts that are now upstream
Regen tlsexttestc.c.patch
Regen aeadtest.c.patch

New test coverage for RC4

From Joshua Sing

Prepare to provide OPENSSL_cleanup.

OPENSSL_cleanup() cleans up and deallocates memory in use by the library.
There are a couple of use cases for this, primarily related to memory
leak testing. This will not be called automatically in LibreSSL, which
means that OpenSSL's OPENSSL_NO_INIT_ATEXIT is implied. If code wants to
clean up then they need to explicitly call this themselves.

ok tb@

Provide c2i_ASN1_ENUMERATED_cbs() and call it from asn1_c2i_primitive().

This avoids asn1_c2i_primitive() from needing knowledge about the internals
of ASN1_INTEGER and ASN1_ENUMERATED.

ok tb@

Ensure ASN.1 types are appropriately encoded.

Per X.690, some ASN.1 types must be primitive encoded, some must be
constructed and some may be either. Add this data to our types table
and check the encoding against this information when decoding.

ok tb@
Ensure a constructed ASN.1 INTEGER is considered invalid when decoding.
Remove duplicate prototype that just snuck in.

Avoid recycling ASN1_STRINGs when decoding ASN.1.

Rather than recycling an existing ASN1_STRING and changing its type, free
it and allocate a replacement. This simplifies the code and potentially
avoids bugs resulting from reuse.

ok tb@

Tidy up asn1_c2i_primitive() slightly.

Rename some variables and consistently goto error.

ok tb@
Rewrap some lines, no functional change.

Mechanically expand IMPLEMENT_BLOCK_CIPHER macro.

These macros make the ASN.1 macros seem sane - there are layers and layers
and layers here, which are hiding bugs.

No change to generated assembly.

Discussed with tb@

Mechanically expand IMPLEMENT_BLOCK_CIPHER macro.

No change to generated assembly.

Mechanically expand IMPLEMENT_BLOCK_CIPHER macro.

Only change to generated assembly is due to EVPerror()'s use of line
numbers.
CVS ----------------------------------------------------------------------

Mechanically expand IMPLEMENT_BLOCK_CIPHER macro.

No change in generated assembly.

Mechanically expand IMPLEMENT_BLOCK_CIPHER macro.

Only change to generated assembly is due to EVPerror()'s use of line
numbers.

Remove now unused IMPLEMENT_BLOCK_CIPHER macro.

Also remove various comments noting that it cannot be used for certain
block ciphers (which kinda defeats the purpose of having a generic
implementation in the first place).

Mechanically expand IMPLEMENT_CFBR macros.

Only change to generated assembly is due to the use of EVPerror().

Make ssl_create_cipher_list() have a single exit

This simplifies memory management and makes it easier to see the leak
that were introduced in the previous commit. Sprinkle a few malloc
errors for consistency.

CID 278396

with/ok jsing
Remove now unused IMPLEMENT_CFBR macro.

Mechanically expand BLOCK_CIPHER_* ciphers.

This includes the wonderful BLOCK_CIPHER_ecb_loop - a for loop in a macro.

No change in generated assembly.

Mechanically expand BLOCK_CIPHER_* macros.

No change in generated assembly.
Update for new rc4_test

commits.message:
Add a nicely licensed, table-driven test for SHA

This tests covers the NIST vectors for SHA-{1,224,256,384,256} and will
soon be able to replace the old SHA tests entirely.

From Joshua Sing <joshua () hypera ! dev>
Link sha test to regress

Check sk_SSL_CIPHER_push() return value

CID 24797

ok jsing

Add tests for 1 million repeated "a"

From Joshua Sing
Unhook old SHA tests

Retire old SHA tests

The old tests were incomplete, some of them had no license and the code
quality was questionable. The new tests by Joshua Sing cover what they
did (and additionally SHA-224 and SHA-384). Many thanks!

Simplify and clean up the ecdsa test a little. Use stdio instead of BIO
for output, use 'err' as a label and avoid some silly repetitions.
Make test tables static const and fix a style nit
Add two const

New md4/md5 regress tests

These exercise MD4 and MD5 with the test vectors from RFCs 1320 and 1321.

From Joshua Sing <joshua () hypera ! dev>
Link new md test to regress.
Unhook the old md4 and md5 tests
Retire the old crap. Thanks, Joshua

Rewrite RMD-160 tests to be table-driven.

From Joshua Sing

Stop using CBIGNUM_it internal to libcrypto.

CBIGNUM_it is supposed to be the "clear bignum" or "secure" bignum - that
is one which zeros its memory after use and ensures that the constant time
flags are set... in LibreSSL we always do both of these things for BIGNUMs,
so just use BIGNUM_it instead.

ok tb@
Adjust for Joshua Sing's test replacements
